<node TEXT="5 plants that attract benificial insects" ID="ID_1191748819" CREATED="1375678301402" MODIFIED="1429466624831">
<font NAME="SansSerif" SIZE="10" BOLD="true"/>
<node TEXT="Sweet alyssum attracts hoverflies and lacewings. The adults of both species feed on nectar and pollen, then lay eggs that hatch in a few days. It&#x2019;s the larvae of these species that destroy garden pests, hunting the undersides of leaves and devouring soft-bodied insects like aphids, mites, and small caterpillars. Read more at http://www.realfarmacy.com/five-awesome-plants-that-attract-beneficial-insects-to-your-garden/#UDHoHUAAiSPzYzkg.99 " ID="ID_1170499652" CREATED="1375678370809" MODIFIED="1375678373799"/>
<node TEXT="Dill, when allowed to flower, attracts many beneficial insects including parasitic wasps. These are not the kind that sting, but tiny solitary wasps barely noticeable to the naked eye. Like hoverflies, parasitic wasps feed on flower nectar. Then they lay eggs inside pest species like aphids, certain beetles, scale insects, and caterpillars. Several other plants in the carrot family (Apiaceae) such as coriander and fennel also attract parasitic wasps and other predators like damsel bugs. Read more at http://www.realfarmacy.com/five-awesome-plants-that-attract-beneficial-insects-to-your-garden/#UDHoHUAAiSPzYzkg.99 " ID="ID_1077242309" CREATED="1375678389024" MODIFIED="1375678391415"/>
<node TEXT="Amaranthus attracts ground beetles and big-eyed bugs, fast-moving predators of slugs, grubs, small caterpillars, flea beetles, and mites. Both the adult and larvae of these beneficial insects are predacious. Amaranthus and other low-growing foliage plants provide just the kind of cover that predatory beetles like, and they provide ornamental value as well.  Read more at http://www.realfarmacy.com/five-awesome-plants-that-attract-beneficial-insects-to-your-garden/#UDHoHUAAiSPzYzkg.99 " ID="ID_1864134917" CREATED="1375678404632" MODIFIED="1375678407214"/>
<node TEXT="Sunflowers attract parasitic wasps and pirate bugs, among other beneficial insects. Minute pirate bugs are interesting little creatures and very useful in sustainable agriculture, often released in greenhouses to control thrips. Both larvae and adults feed on small insects such as psyllids, thrips, mites, aphids, whiteflies, and small caterpillars. Read more at http://www.realfarmacy.com/five-awesome-plants-that-attract-beneficial-insects-to-your-garden/#UDHoHUAAiSPzYzkg.99 " ID="ID_64708588" CREATED="1375678417351" MODIFIED="1375678419550"/>
<node TEXT="French marigolds are more useful for attracting pollinators, especially honeybees. However, they also attract hoverflies and may help to deter soil nematodes. Marigolds also attract butterflies, which may have no benefit to the vegetable garden but are a joy to see fluttering around in your sustainable landscape. Read more at http://www.realfarmacy.com/five-awesome-plants-that-attract-beneficial-insects-to-your-garden/#UDHoHUAAiSPzYzkg.99 " ID="ID_586008108" CREATED="1375678428399" MODIFIED="1375678430566"/>
